\begin_layout Subsection
The One-Good Real Small Open Economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
perfect
\series default
 capital mobility is assumed (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r=r^{*}$
\end_inset

), where 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the world real interest rate (UIP).
 Same as for households, the income is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Income=Y_{t}+T_{t}
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents transfers from abroad.
 The current budget constraint is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}-C_{t}+rB_{t}+T_{t}=B_{t+1}-B_{t}+\Delta R
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 Government Spending
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $rB_{t}$
\end_inset

 Net Factor Payments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 Net Tansfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}-C_{t}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $EX_{t}-IM_{t}$
\end_inset

 - Net Exports)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta R$
\end_inset

 Central Bank Reserves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which means: saving is the increase in foreign assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, we temporarily assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta R=0$
\end_inset

, which yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CA_{t}=B_{t+1}-B_{t}=F_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(current account balance = saving abroad = net financial outflow).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the consumption discussion (with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=\frac{r}{1+r}PV_{t}(Y)+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Economy Shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To better understand a model, it is always good to 
\series bold
shock
\series default
 it and see the reaction.
 Consider a 
\series bold
temporary
\series default
 deviation in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Output can't be stored:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=Y(1+a_{t})
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the optimal consumption will be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=\frac{r}{1+r}\left[1+a_{t}+\frac{1}{1+r}+\frac{1}{(1+r)^{2}}+\cdots\right]Y+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=Y+\frac{r}{1+r}a_{t}Y+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Same as in lecture 1, the 
\series bold
marginal propensity to consume
\series default
 is used to address the extra income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CA can now be computed for this case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CA_{t}=Y_{t}+rB_{t}-C_{t}\Rightarrow CA_{t}=\frac{1}{1+t}a_{t}Y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is the 
\series bold
permanent income hypothesis
\series default
 for the whole economy.
 Given a temporary deviation in the output from its normal level, the consumptio
n is smoothed according to the marginal propensity to consume.
 Everything that was said regarding the individuals is true for a whole
 economy as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the shock is permanent, what would happen to the CA? All the additional
 income will be consumed, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta CA=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Those who save are pessimistic, while those who borrow are optimistic
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sign of the CA represents output vs.
 uses of output.
\end_layout

