\begin_layout Subsection
The Closed Economy Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an open economy, imbalance between supply and demand is possible - which
 is not true for a closed economy, where supply and demand must always be
 in an equilibrium (examples: North Korea, The World).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this model, the interest rate is 
\series bold
endogenous
\series default
, and might deviate form 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Now a specific utility function is required.
 Assuming:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(C_{t},z_{t})=(1+z_{t})lnC_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the schock to utility and marginal utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the supply side - output is exogenous and 
\series bold
can't be stored
\series default
.
 Same as with open economy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=T(1+a_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the production shock, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the normal output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output always equals income (in a closed economy - in an open one there
 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $rB_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Euler equations are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1+z_{t}}{C_{t}}=\frac{1}{1+\rho}\left(\frac{1+z_{t+1}}{C_{t+1}}\right)(1+r_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1+z_{t+1}}{C_{t+1}}=\frac{1}{1+\rho}\left(\frac{1+z_{t+2}}{C_{1+2}}\right)(1+r_{t+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question is: how a shock affets 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

? The intuition for the answer is: supply-demand for funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}>0$
\end_inset

 increases saving, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}\downarrow$
\end_inset

 (by permanent income hypothesis - production increases income, people try
 to save it).
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

This period is good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, everyone goes to the bank, the bank pays less.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}>0$
\end_inset

 increases borrowing, leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}\uparrow$
\end_inset

 (everyone wants to borrow, there is not enough money to borrow, interest
 rate goes up).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium output can't be stored, thus: 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=Y(1+a_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 Knowing the quantities, we can find the prices and determine the effect
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1+z_{t}}{Y(1+a_{t})}=\frac{1}{1+\rho}\left(\frac{1+z_{t+1}}{Y(1+a_{t+1})}\right)(1+r_{t})\Rightarrow1+r_{t}=(1+\rho)\frac{(1+z_{t})(1+a_{t+1})}{(1+a_{t})(1+z_{t+1})}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What happens to the interest rate if the income and the consumption shocks
 are equals? - They cancel out (intuition: borrowing and saving effects
 are equal in size 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow r_{t}=\rho$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important notice: future and current shocks of the same type have opposite
 effects (why?).
 For example, higher 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 - higher consumption 
\series bold
today
\series default
.
 Higher 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 - better to save.
\end_layout

